{
  "texts": [
    "These included unsupervised and supervised quantification.",
    "In unsupervised quantification, the dataset shift is assumed to be a pure class-distribution shift.",
    "Alternatively, the dataset shift is assumed to be 'small' and the unlabeled set of target samples is used to align the internal feature representation of a machine learning algorithm.",
    "In supervised quantification, no explicit assumptions are made on the dataset shift, but it is assumed that a small amount of samples are available in the target domain.",
    "González et al. (2017) proposed a methodology to assess the efficacy of learned models, which takes into account the fact that the data distribution (the plankton composition of the sample) might vary between the training phase and the testing phase."
  ]
}